<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="mobile-ux">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>Mobile-first design with 44x44pt (iOS) / 48x48dp (Android) touch targets, thumb zone placement, and Core Web Vitals. One primary action per screen.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>mobile</tag>
      <tag>ux-design</tag>
      <tag>touch-targets</tag>
      <tag>performance</tag>
      <tag>core-web-vitals</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Mobile UX Design Basics</title>

    <summary>Mobile UX requires mobile-first design (smallest screen first, then enhance), touch targets of at least 44x44pt (iOS) or 48x48dp (Android), primary actions in the thumb zone (bottom third of screen), and Core Web Vitals targets of LCP &lt; 2.5s / CLS &lt; 0.1. Navigation defaults to bottom tab bar (3-5 items); hamburger menus are secondary. One primary action per screen is a hard constraint.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Desktop designs scaled down to mobile produce tiny targets, broken layouts, and slow load times that cause abandonment. Mobile context differs fundamentally: partial attention, variable connectivity, touch input, smaller screen. Mobile-first design forces prioritization of essential content and interaction, which also improves the desktop version. 53% of users abandon pages that take more than 3 seconds to load on mobile.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a product or feature that must run on mobile (apply mobile-first from the design phase).</item>
        <item>Auditing an existing web product for mobile usability issues before a campaign or launch.</item>
        <item>Reviewing PRs that add UI components to ensure touch targets, input types, and thumb-zone placement are correct.</item>
        <item>Before App Store or Google Play submission — checklist sweep against HIG and Material Design guidelines.</item>
        <item>Performance audit for mobile: LCP, FID, CLS targets are more critical on mobile than desktop.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Internal tools used exclusively on desktop (admin panels, dashboards accessed via VPN).</item>
        <item>Projects where mobile is explicitly out of scope for the current phase.</item>
        <item>Prototyping in high fidelity before mobile constraints are validated — wireframe mobile flows first.</item>
        <item>Accessibility-only audits — mobile UX overlaps but is not a replacement for dedicated a11y review.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="mobile-first-principle">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Design for the smallest screen first. Identify the core content and single primary action for mobile. Add enhancements for tablet and desktop. Never start from desktop and scale down.</statement>
        <rationale>Scaling down a desktop design produces tiny targets, broken layouts, and stripped-out content. Starting from mobile forces honest prioritization — if something is important enough to show on mobile, it belongs; if not, it is secondary content for larger screens.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>One primary action per screen is a hard constraint, not a guideline. Two equally weighted CTAs on a mobile screen must be split into separate screens or redesigned to establish clear primary/secondary hierarchy.</statement>
        <rationale>Mobile users have partial attention and small screens. Competing actions produce decision paralysis and reduce conversion. The constraint forces product discipline about what matters most at each step.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="touch-target-requirements">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Minimum touch target size: 44x44pt on iOS, 48x48dp on Android. Minimum spacing between adjacent targets: 8px. These are hard minimums, not recommendations.</statement>
        <rationale>Touch input is imprecise. Targets below minimum size produce tap errors, frustration, and accessibility failures. Adjacent targets without spacing cause accidental activation of the wrong element.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Place primary actions in the thumb zone — the bottom third of the screen for one-handed use. Place destructive or rarely-needed actions at the top (hard to reach).</statement>
        <rationale>Thumb zone models from Steven Hoober's research show 75% of mobile interaction uses one hand. Bottom-zone placement reduces reach error and fatigue for primary actions. Top placement for destructive actions provides natural friction.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="navigation-patterns">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use bottom tab bar (3-5 items) as the primary navigation pattern for mobile apps. Reserve hamburger menus for secondary or overflow navigation only.</statement>
        <rationale>Bottom tab bars consistently outperform hamburger menus on discoverability in usability studies. Hamburgers hide navigation behind a tap, reducing awareness of available sections and increasing navigation errors.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="form-optimization">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set correct input type attributes on all form fields: type="email" for email, type="tel" for phone, type="number" for numeric input, type="search" for search. Never disable zoom (user-scalable=no).</statement>
        <rationale>Correct input types trigger the right mobile keyboard, reducing form errors significantly. Disabling zoom is an accessibility violation and is blocked by Safari since iOS 10.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="performance-targets">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Target Core Web Vitals: LCP &lt; 2.5s, FID &lt; 100ms, CLS &lt; 0.1, TTI &lt; 5s. Serve WebP images with srcset/sizes. Lazy-load below-fold content. Never serve retina images to low-bandwidth connections without srcset.</statement>
        <rationale>53% of mobile users abandon pages taking over 3 seconds. Each 1-second delay reduces conversions by ~7%. CLS above 0.1 causes mis-taps when content shifts during load. WebP with srcset reduces image payload by 25-35% vs JPEG without quality loss.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ios-vs-android-differences">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Design platform-specific interaction patterns where they differ: iOS uses bottom tabs and swipe-from-edge back navigation; Android uses bottom nav bar and back gesture or button. Never assume one platform's gesture behavior on the other.</statement>
        <rationale>Users have trained gestures from their OS. Swipe-from-left-edge is iOS back navigation; on Android it may trigger a drawer. Building cross-platform patterns without accounting for these differences causes gesture conflicts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>iOS: bottom tab bar, back via left-edge swipe, sheets from bottom, 44pt targets.</item>
        <item>Android: bottom navigation, back via gesture or system button, full-screen dialogs, 48dp targets.</item>
        <item>iOS: right side for primary actions; Android: Floating Action Button for primary creation action.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="standard-gesture-vocabulary">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use only standard platform gestures. Always provide a visible alternative (button or link) for every gesture-based action. Never invent non-standard gestures without visible affordances.</statement>
        <rationale>Custom gestures are undiscoverable. Users have no way to know they exist without explicit hints. Standard gestures work because users have learned them from the OS; novel gestures require onboarding that most users skip.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Tap: select or activate.</item>
        <item>Long press: context menu or selection mode.</item>
        <item>Swipe horizontal: navigate between views or reveal row actions.</item>
        <item>Swipe vertical: scroll.</item>
        <item>Pinch: zoom.</item>
        <item>Pull down: refresh (always pair with a visible refresh button).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="progressive-enhancement-tiers">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Build mobile as the baseline with core functionality and touch-optimization. Add tablet enhancements (side panels, more visible content). Add desktop enhancements (full navigation, multi-column, keyboard shortcuts) only after mobile baseline is complete.</statement>
        <rationale>Enhancement tiers prevent mobile from being treated as a stripped-down desktop version. The mobile tier is complete and functional on its own; larger screens receive additive enhancements, not different products.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="mobile-accessibility">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Support VoiceOver (iOS) and TalkBack (Android). Respect system text-size settings — never use absolute units that break at 150-200% text scale. Respect prefers-reduced-motion for animations.</statement>
        <rationale>15% of users rely on screen readers at some point. Large text size settings are common among older users and low-vision users. Breaking text scaling or ignoring reduced-motion preferences excludes significant user populations.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Shrinking desktop design to fit mobile viewport instead of redesigning for mobile context.</description>
        <reason>Produces tiny touch targets, cramped layouts, and forced-zoom content. Mobile is a different context requiring different information hierarchy, not a smaller copy of the desktop layout.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Skeleton screens replaced with generic spinners for content-heavy pages.</description>
        <reason>Skeleton screens reduce perceived load time for known-layout content because they set accurate expectations. Generic spinners with unknown duration increase perceived wait times and anxiety.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>An agent can review UI component specifications (JSX/HTML/CSS) and flag touch-target violations, missing input types, and non-mobile-friendly navigation patterns. It can also run Lighthouse mobile audits via CLI and parse results into actionable tickets. For design files, agents can analyze Figma frame dimensions and component spacing. Human testing on real devices remains the irreplaceable checkpoint — performance and real-touch behavior are not detectable by static analysis.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <p>Agents analyzing CSS cannot detect actual rendered touch target size when styles are computed dynamically (e.g., from parent flex layout) — static analysis gives false positives and false negatives. Lighthouse emulation uses network throttling simulation, not real 3G/4G — real-device results will differ, sometimes significantly. Agents may suggest touch targets are compliant based on CSS width/height, but padding and margin overlap can make adjacent targets effectively smaller — visual review required. Mobile-first means designing the mobile layout first, not just adding @media (max-width) breakpoints after — agents reviewing CSS-only may miss layout logic in JS components. Android and iOS differ on swipe-back gesture behavior — a recommended gesture interaction for one platform may break on the other; agents should flag platform-specific patterns.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>lighthouse CLI: Automated mobile performance and best-practice audit (npm i -g lighthouse, github.com/GoogleChrome/lighthouse). puppeteer: Headless Chrome with mobile device emulation for screenshot and interaction testing (npm i puppeteer, pptr.dev). axe-core CLI: Accessibility audit including mobile-relevant rules (touch targets, focus) (npm i -g @axe-core/cli, github.com/dequelabs/axe-core). imagemin-cli: Batch optimize images for mobile (WebP conversion, compression) (npm i -g imagemin-cli, github.com/imagemin/imagemin-cli). size-limit: Enforce JS bundle size budget for mobile performance (npm i -D size-limit, github.com/ai/size-limit).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <p>BrowserStack (SaaS): Real device cloud; agent can trigger test runs on specific devices and retrieve screenshots. Sauce Labs (SaaS): Similar to BrowserStack; supports Appium for native app testing. Firebase Test Lab (SaaS): Google-hosted real device lab; integrates with CI/CD for automated mobile tests. Vercel Analytics (SaaS): Core Web Vitals by device type; agent can query mobile-specific CWV scores. PageSpeed Insights API (SaaS): Google CWV data for real users on mobile (https://www.googleapis.com/pagespeedonline/v5/runPagespeed?strategy=mobile). Smartlook (SaaS): Mobile session recordings; visual review required, no structured API for findings.</p>
    </section>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/mobile-audit.sh" purpose="Run Lighthouse mobile audit: runs mobile preset, extracts Core Web Vitals + failed audits. Usage: bash scripts/mobile-audit.sh https://example.com"/>
    </scripts>

